{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T18:22:25.142023", "elapsed_seconds": 7.702, "stage": "INFO", "message": "Generated response from Gemini", "data": {"response": "Based on the provided documentation, here are the differences between Query and Path parameters:\n\n**Query Parameters:**\n*   Are function parameters that are **not part of the path parameters**; they are automatically interpreted as \"query\" parameters (Document 4, 5).\n*   Appear **after the `?` in a URL**, separated by `&` characters (Document 4, 5).\n*   Are **not a fixed part of a path**, meaning they can be optional and can have default values (Document 7).\n*   Can be declared as optional by setting their default to `None` (Document 17).\n*   Singular values are interpreted as query parameters by default, so you don't always need to explicitly add `Query` (Document 6).\n*   Can be explicitly defined with `Query` to receive a list of values or multiple values (Document 11, 12).\n\n**Path Parameters:**\n*   Are parameters that are **part of the URL path** itself (Document 4, 5, 16, 20).\n*   Are declared using `Path` (Document 1, 14, 15).\n*   Are **always required** as they have to be part of the path (Document 16).\n\n**Similarities:**\n*   Both `Query` and `Path` can be used to declare validations and metadata (Document 1, 16, 18, 19).\n*   Both can declare numeric validations like `gt`, `ge`, `lt`, `le` (Document 18, 19).", "response_length": 1233, "tokens_used": 203, "sources_extracted": ["Source: docs\\tutorial\\path-params-numeric-validations.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\cookie-params.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\header-params.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\query-params.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\body-multiple-params.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\path-params.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\query-param-models.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\query-params-str-validations.md", "Source: docs\\reference\\parameters.md"]}}
